Blocky

Target IP: 10.129.180.68

Scanning



There are three TCP ports open on the target machine: FTP, SSH, and HTTP. The vhost name of this target host is blocky.htb. I appended this to the /etc/hosts.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed when browsing to this application. The target host is running WordPress 4.8 application.


Running wpscan --url http://blocky.htb --enumerate u shows there is an interesting user called notch. However, trying to crack the password of this user did not work.


Performing a directory search lead to some interesting result as shown above. Performing a directory search search on wiki did not show any other directories.


The /plugins is interesting as it is not /wordpress/wp-content/plugins. I decompiled both of these JAR files using an online decompiler. The BlockyCore.jar is an interesting file as it contains a single java class file called BlockyCore.java.


And this file contains the username and password as shown above. Now I have the credentials, I can spray this against the SSH and FTP.

Exploitation


Using the username root did not work with the password 8YsqfCTnvxAUeduzjNSXe22. However, from previous enumeration, I identified a user called notch in the WordPress application. Spraying notch:8YsqfCTnvxAUeduzjNSXe22 worked against the SSH application!

Privilege Escalation


Looks like notch can run all commands using sudo. Now I have a root shell by using sudo bash.

Flags


The user.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine using SSH as notch.

The root.txt flag once I spawned a root shell.
